+# Surface Portability Notes
+
+This lesson currently contains one universal baseline instruction file, one
+path-scoped instruction file, one agent definition, and supporting lesson docs.
+No prompt files, MCP configuration, hooks, or skills were discovered in this
+lesson snapshot.
+
+## Discovered Instruction Architecture
+
+| Artifact | Role in this lesson | Portability |
+| --- | --- | --- |
+| `.github/copilot-instructions.md` | Universal baseline for project context and core conventions | Portable across CLI, Chat, inline completions, coding agent, and code review |
+| `.github/instructions/api.instructions.md` | Path-scoped route guidance with `applyTo` | Surface-specific: VS Code and coding-agent style scoped loading |
+| `.github/agents/reviewer.agent.md` | Reviewer role and checklist | Surface-specific: agent-enabled experiences, not universal |
+| `docs/portability-matrix.md` | Explicit feature support matrix | Reference doc, portable as documentation rather than auto-loaded instruction |
+| `docs/cli-guide.md` | CLI loading model and limitations | Reference doc for CLI behavior |
+| `README.md` and `docs/surface-strategy-example.md` | Lesson goals, constraints, and expected outputs | Reference docs |
+
+## Surface Comparison
+
+| Surface | Universal baseline | Scoped instructions | Agents | Docs |
+| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
+| VS Code Chat | Uses `.github/copilot-instructions.md` | Can use `applyTo`-scoped instruction files when relevant | Can use agent definitions | Can read lesson docs directly |
+| VS Code Inline | Uses `.github/copilot-instructions.md` | Best surface for `applyTo`-scoped instruction files | Does not use agents | May benefit from nearby file context, not full doc workflows |
+| GitHub CLI | Uses `.github/copilot-instructions.md` | Does not load `.github/instructions/*.instructions.md` | Does not load agents | Relies on discovery or indexed docs rather than auto-loading |
+| Coding Agent | Uses `.github/copilot-instructions.md` | Can use scoped instruction files | Can use agent-oriented layers | Can use docs as supporting context |
+| Code Review | Uses `.github/copilot-instructions.md` | Should not rely on scoped instruction files | Should not rely on agents | May use docs as reference, but not as guaranteed baseline |
+
+## Portable vs Surface-Specific Features
+
+### Portable
+
+- Repository-level baseline rules in `.github/copilot-instructions.md`
+- Deep reference material in `docs/*.md` when the surface can search or attach
+  docs
+- Cross-surface conventions such as ESM-only modules, Vitest, structured JSON
+  errors, fail-closed audit ordering, and no `console.log()`
+
+### Surface-Specific
+
+- `.github/instructions/*.instructions.md` path scoping through `applyTo`
+- `.github/agents/*.agent.md` role and tool specialization
+- Prompt files, MCP configuration, hooks, and skills when they exist
+
+For this lesson, `.github/copilot-instructions.md` is the canonical source for
+must-follow universal guidance. `docs/portability-matrix.md` is the canonical
+reference for support boundaries because it explicitly maps features to
+surfaces.
+
+## Concrete Portability Risk
+
+A team could place a critical route rule only in
+`.github/instructions/api.instructions.md`, then see strong results in inline
+completions and coding-agent flows while CLI and code review miss the rule
+entirely. That creates inconsistent output across surfaces even though the team
+believes the rule is "in Copilot."
+
+## False Positive
+
+A reviewer might claim the CLI ignored route-template guidance because a CLI
+response did not include the exact `authenticate -> authorize -> validate`
+pattern from `api.instructions.md`. In this lesson that is a false positive:
+the missing behavior is explained by surface loading limits, not by a failure to
+follow the portable baseline.
+
+## Hard Negative
+
+Treat it as a hard negative when critical compliance or security guidance lives
+only in a non-portable layer such as `.github/agents/reviewer.agent.md` or a
+future prompt, MCP, or hook file. If the rule must affect CLI, inline, coding
+agent, and code review behavior, it cannot live only in a surface-specific
+artifact.
+
+## Where Each Kind of Guidance Should Live
+
+- Put universal, must-follow project rules in `.github/copilot-instructions.md`.
+- Put file-pattern or subsystem-specific instructions in
+  `.github/instructions/*.instructions.md`.
+- Put role-based review or workflow specialization in `.github/agents/*.agent.md`.
+- Put explanatory knowledge, rationale, and comparison tables in `docs/*.md`.
+- Put prompts, MCP setup, and hooks only in surface-specific layers where their
+  added power is worth the reduced portability.
+
+## Recommended Operating Model
+
+Start with the universal baseline, then add narrower layers only when the extra
+precision is worth the portability trade-off. When artifacts disagree, keep the
+portable rule in `.github/copilot-instructions.md` authoritative and use scoped
+instructions, agents, and docs as layered enhancements rather than replacements.
